It’s been a while since I’ve done any running. It felt good (and bad 😂) to get in a 5K on the treadmill. 

The first half mile felt pretty crappy (I didn’t warm-up so my body had to adjust). The middle 2 miles felt great. The last .6 mile I wanted to be done. I was skipping almost every song on my playlist, thinking about how much faster I used to be and I was bored. 

Not every workout feels great. Sometimes you just work through the hard bits, because you know that the effort is worth it. Your health is worth it. 

Even though I didn’t love every second of this workout, I’m glad I did it. I feel physically and mentally stronger for pushing through it. 

If you have hard moments this week (workout or otherwise) remember that you are strong and capable of pushing through. Success doesn’t come from being motivated every second of every day. It comes from determination and consistency. 

If you have any song suggestions for my running list, please feel free to share. 🎶

5-years rocking the same swimsuit. 👙

I was pregnant in the far left and middle photos. The far right photo is today. 

It makes me realize, I haven’t bought myself a swimsuit in a LONG time. Which isn’t a big deal, but it also reminds me that I have a tendency to take care of everyone around me first. 

Luckily, I have a husband and family that encourages me to take time for myself. I’m just not always the best at actually putting that into motion (outside of exercise, which is part of my job). I have two spa/massage gift cards and a nail salon gift card that have been waiting for me to use for over a year now. 🥴

Over a lot of years of teaching group classes, MANY students have told me they dread Side Planks in my workouts. So, why do I keep including them?

I tried to get on the treadmill today and it was broken. 

Which was very frustrating, because I was feeling tired and bloated, and it took a lot of mental effort for me to get myself down there for my workout. 

Instead of getting in a run I ended up calling about my treadmill repair (it’s still under warranty so they are sending a new console). 

Here’s the thing: sometimes things get in the way of our plans and efforts. That’s just a part of life. You can’t control these unexpected occurrences. All you can control is the way you respond. 

So, I will get in my run outside later tonight. Luckily, this evening is open so that’s an option. 

Don’t let the little things throw you off course. Over and over again I see people start strong and quit their workout routine at the first interruption or obstacle. 

Getting in exercise won’t always be convenient, but you can choose to make it a consistent priority. 

In the long run, missing a workout (or a week of workouts) won’t have a long term impact IF you keep showing up. 

So make the choice to show up for your health and keep showing up for it. Then make that decision over and over again on a regular basis.

Flexibility and stability are two components to building a strong and healthy body. 

Often, when people focus purely on strength training they have a lot of stability, and less mobility (especially in the hips and shoulders). ***I said often, because you can focus on mobility during strength training, but it requires intention and understanding about ranges/planes of motion.

If you focus only on flexibility you can be more prone to injury because you don’t have the joint stability to protect yourself from injury, or to maintain good form during exercise. 

To build your healthiest body, you should incorporate both strength and mobility training. You want to have full mobility without pain, but enough stability to protect yourself from injury. 

Do you feel like you have a good balance between strength and mobility?
